## [1] 0
#making a copy
amescleaned <- ames
#remove the observations with less than 10 observations
factor_vars <- sapply(amescleaned, is.factor)
for (var in names(amescleaned)[factor_vars]) {
  table_var <- table(amescleaned[[var]])
  small_categories <- names(table_var[table_var < 10])

  if (length(small_categories) > 0) {
    cat(paste("Removing observations with", var, "in categories:", paste(small_categories, collapse = ", "), "\n"))
    amescleaned <- amescleaned[!(amescleaned[[var]] %in% small_categories), ]
    amescleaned <- droplevels(amescleaned)
  }
}

#bagging OOB AUC


set.seed(42)
B <- 500
pred <- matrix(NA, nrow(amescopy), B)

for (i in 1:B) {
    set.seed(i)  # Ensure reproducibility
    train_idx <- sample(nrow(amescopy), nrow(amescopy), replace = TRUE)
    oob_idx <- setdiff(1:nrow(amescopy), train_idx)
    train <- amescopy[train_idx, ]
    oob <- amescopy[oob_idx, ]
   
    cart_B <- rpart(expensive ~ . ,
                  cp = 0, data = train, method = "class")  # unpruned is required

OOB AUC from RandomForest

# OOB AUC from RandomForest
set.seed(42)

B <- 500
n <- nrow(amescopy)
p <- sqrt(ncol(amescopy) - 1)  # One column for the response variable
pred_rf <- matrix(NA, nrow = n, ncol = B)

for (i in 1:B) {
    #set.seed(i)  # Ensure reproducibility
    train_idx <- sample(n, n, replace = TRUE)
    oob_idx <- setdiff(1:n, train_idx)
    
    # Randomly select a subset of variables, considering at least one of each category for diversity
    vars <- sample(colnames(amescopy[, -which(colnames(amescopy) == "expensive")]), size = ceiling(p), replace = FALSE)
    formula <- as.formula(paste("expensive ~", paste(vars, collapse = "+")))
    
    train <- amescopy[train_idx, ]
    oob <- amescopy[oob_idx, ]
   
    cart_rf <- rpart(formula, data = train, method = "class", cp = 0)  # unpruned
    pred_rf[oob_idx, i] <- predict(cart_rf, oob, type = "prob")[, 2]
}

# Calculate OOB AUC
phat_rf <- rowMeans(pred_rf, na.rm = TRUE, dims = 1)
pred_rocr_rf <- prediction(phat_rf, amescopy$expensive)
auc_ROCR_rf <- performance(pred_rocr_rf, measure = "auc")
auc_ROCR_rf@y.values[[1]]

Getting Test AUC for Random Forest

#Getting Test AUC for Random Forest
library(pROC)
library(doParallel)

num_cores <- detectCores() - 1

cl <- makeCluster(num_cores)
registerDoParallel(cl)

n = nrow(amescopy)

AUC_test <- foreach(i = 1:100, .combine = c,
               .packages = c('randomForest', 'pROC')) %dopar% {
    set.seed(i)
    train_idx <- sample(n, n*0.8, replace = FALSE)
    test_idx <- setdiff(1:n, train_idx)
    
    train <- amescopy[train_idx, ]
    test <- amescopy[test_idx, ]
    
    rf_model_test <- randomForest(expensive ~ ., data = train, ntree = 500)
    phat <- predict(rf_model_test, test, type = "prob")[, 2]
    
    roc_curve <- roc(test$expensive, phat)
    auc(roc_curve)
}

stopCluster(cl)

#plot result based 95% CI
plot(AUC_test, pch = 19, col = "blue", xlab = "Iteration", ylab = "AUC", main = "AUC on Test Set")
abline(h = mean(AUC_test), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "red")
abline(h = quantile(AUC_test, 0.025), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "green")
abline(h = quantile(AUC_test, 0.975), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "green")

#calculate the mean AUC
mean(AUC_test)
## [1] 0.9868362

Comments: The test AUC and OOB AUC from randomforest are almost exactly the same, with OOB AUC marginally better

##LPM Classicfication with AUC

#LPM Classicfication with AUC
numeric_vars <- sapply(amescleaned, is.numeric)

#create numeric only dataset
amescopy_numeric <- amescopy[, numeric_vars]

set.seed(42)

auc_lpm <- c()

# Calculate AUC for lpm
 for (j in 1:500) {
      ind <- unique(sample(nrow(amescopy), nrow(amescopy), replace = TRUE)) #boostrapping 100 times
      
      train <- amescopy[ind, ]  #
      inner_test <- amescopy[-ind, ]  # Create a separate test set for the inner loop
      
      model_lpm <- lm(expensive ~ ., data = train)
      phat_lpm <- predict(model_lpm, inner_test, type = "response")
      phat_lpm <- pmin(1, pmax(0, phat_lpm))
      
      #AUC
      pred_rocr_lpm <- prediction(phat_lpm, inner_test$expensive)  # Remove indexing [,1]
      aur_rocr_lpm <- performance(pred_rocr_lpm, "auc")
      auc_lpm[j] <- aur_rocr_lpm@y.values[[1]]
    }

##plot result based 95% CI

#plot result based 95% CI
plot(auc_lpm, pch = 19, col = "blue", xlab = "Iteration", ylab = "AUC", main = "AUC on Test Set")
abline(h = mean(auc_lpm), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "red")
abline(h = quantile(auc_lpm, 0.025), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "green")
abline(h = quantile(auc_lpm, 0.975), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "green")

Bagging OOB MSPE

library(rpart)

m <- 100 # how many times we want to run the loop

mspe_st <- c()

set.seed(42)

for (i in 1:m) {
  
  set.seed(i)  
  reg_train_idx <- sample(nrow(amescopy2), nrow(amescopy2), replace = TRUE)
  reg_oob_idx <- setdiff(1:nrow(amescopy2), reg_train_idx)
  
  reg_train <- amescopy2[reg_train_idx, ]
  reg_oob <- amescopy2[reg_oob_idx, ]
  
   # Single pruned tree

  fit_reg <- rpart(Sale_Price ~ ., data = reg_train, method = "anova")
  yhat_reg <- predict(fit_reg, reg_oob)
  
  #RMSPE
  mspe_st[i] <- mean((reg_oob$Sale_Price - yhat_reg) ^ 2)
}

#mean
mean(mspe_st)
## [1] 0.03727854
#sd

Getting Test MSPE for Random Forest

#Getting Test AUC for Random Forest
library(pROC)
library(doParallel)

num_cores <- detectCores() - 1

cl <- makeCluster(num_cores)
registerDoParallel(cl)

n = nrow(amescopy2)

rmspe_test <- foreach(i = 1:50, .combine = c,
               .packages = c('randomForest', 'pROC')) %dopar% {
    set.seed(i)
    train_idx_rf_te <- sample(n, n, replace = TRUE)
    test_idx_rf_te <- setdiff(1:n, train_idx_rf_te)
    
    train_reg_te <- amescopy2[train_idx_rf_te, ]
    test_reg_te <- amescopy2[test_idx_rf_te, ]
    
    rf_model_test_te <- randomForest(Sale_Price ~ ., data = train_reg_te, ntree = 500)
  
  yhat_reg_rf_te <- predict(rf_model_test_te, test_reg_te)
  
  #MSPE
  return(mean((test_reg_te$Sale_Price - yhat_reg_rf_te) ^ 2))
}

stopCluster(cl)

Linear Regression Benchmark

#LPM regression with mspe

set.seed(42)

# Calculate mspe for lpm
m <- 500 # how many times we want to run the loop


mspe_lm_reg <- c()


  for (i in 1:m) {
    
    # set.seed(i)  # Ensure reproducibility
    set.seed(i)
    ind_lpm_reg <- sample(nrow(amescopy2), nrow(amescopy2)*0.8, replace = FALSE)
    train_lpm_reg <- amescopy2[ind_lpm_reg, ]
    test_lpm_reg <- amescopy2[-ind_lpm_reg, ]
    
    #linear model
    fit_lm_reg <- lm(Sale_Price ~ ., data = train_lpm_reg)
    yhat_lm_reg <- predict(fit_lm_reg, test_lpm_reg)
  
    # MSPE
    mspe_lm_reg[i] <- mean((test_lpm_reg$Sale_Price - yhat_lm_reg) ^ 2)
}
#mean
mean(mspe_lm_reg)
## [1] 0.009574167
#sd
sd(mspe_lm_reg)
## [1] 0.001112148
#plot result based 95% CI
plot(mspe_lm_reg, pch = 19, col = "blue", xlab = "Iteration", ylab = "MSPE", main = "LPM MSPE on Test Set")
abline(h = mean(mspe_lm_reg), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "red")
abline(h = quantile(mspe_lm_reg, 0.025), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "green")
abline(h = quantile(mspe_lm_reg, 0.975), lwd = 2, lty = 2, col = "green")

Comments: LPM MSPE however is the lowest among models thus better than others
